These should be able to catch any sort of regular issue. If one of these test fails, you should be able to 
narrow it down to the object type, and the method that caused the problem.

This is what I would personally use for testing, but it still leaves some of the work to the user. It's mainly
just to make pin-pointing the problem in the LinkedList class easier. 

(Note: If a bunch of tests are failing, then check to see which test failed first. If you still can't fix the issue,
then the class might have a data leak, which if that's the case, god help you. Regardless of the issue, this should 
still be able to find the general area of the problem.)